{
  "texts": [
    "To this end, one can refer to probabilistic models of ranking data, such as the Plackett-Luce (PL) distribution, which assumes a parameter v i > 0 for every choice alternative x i and models the probability of a ranking τ: x 1 x 2.",
    "Now, suppose the PL parameters are specified in a functional form as v = f θ (x), where θ is a parameter vector; a simple example is a log-linear utility function f θ (x) = exp(x, θ).",
    "Then, given training data D = {τ j } N j=1 in the form of (i.i.d.)",
    "rankings τ j: x j,1 x j,2.",
    "x j,m j, the log-likelihood of θ is given by"
  ]
}